  <h2>Part VI. Notable Contacts and References</h2>
  <p>The character and professional references listed by Sapieha on his various US Army personal history statements reveal the calibre of his network:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Maj. Gen. Edwin L. Sibert</strong> &mdash; G-2 (Chief of Intelligence), 12th Army Group. Sapieha&rsquo;s immediate superior and the officer responsible for his work on General Bradley&rsquo;s staff.</li>
    <li><strong>General Omar N. Bradley</strong> &mdash; Commanding General, 12th Army Group; personally authorised Sapieha&rsquo;s travel documents; awarded Sapieha the Bronze Star; wrote personal farewell letter on dissolution of 12th Army Group.</li>
    <li><strong>Brig. Gen. Anthony D. Biddle</strong> &mdash; US diplomat; Military Attach&eacute; to Allied governments-in-exile (including Poland) in London; listed as reference at The Pentagon.</li>
    <li><strong>William H. Jackson</strong> &mdash; J.H. Whitney &amp; Co, 630 Fifth Ave NYC; Deputy Director of the CIA 1950&ndash;1951.</li>
    <li><strong>Arthur Bliss Lane</strong> &mdash; 2440 Massachusetts Ave, Washington DC; US Ambassador to Poland 1944&ndash;1947; resigned in protest over Soviet domination; author of &ldquo;I Saw Poland Betrayed&rdquo; (1948).</li>
    <li><strong>Jan Ciechanowski</strong> &mdash; 6205 29th St NW, Washington DC; Polish Ambassador to the United States 1941&ndash;1945.</li>
    <li><strong>Eric M. Warburg</strong> &mdash; 52 William Street, NYC; prominent international banker (Warburg family).</li>
    <li><strong>General Kazimierz Sosnkowski</strong> &mdash; Commander-in-Chief, Polish Armed Forces 1943&ndash;1944; Sapieha&rsquo;s direct superior during the 1939 campaign and Government-in-Exile period in Paris.</li>
    <li><strong>Anne Fremantle</strong> &mdash; 241 East 49th St, NYC; author and intellectual (listed as credit reference) &mdash; a family connection pointing to the Fremantle family that Paul&rsquo;s daughter Christine would marry into.</li>
  </ul>

